{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"605c2104-2bba-44f8-9159-ea672ae5df5d","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **Reinstalls** the same versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installs but won't pull newer versions to match your updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** After an SDK update, your workload versions are stale, not corrupted. `dotnet workload update` gets the matching versions; `repair` would just reinstall the old ones.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) appears, and reinstall if needed with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5868e921-3a63-401e-a519-03e9bb48ba39","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":302,"requestId":"1011:325178:14DC010:176D9D4:69FD3377"},"id":"d05d758f-0cd0-46f7-b3ab-3a3df6cc65ab","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:51:12.918Z","parentId":"8f0c877d-3d41-4812-bf47-f409f27d587e"}
